message:
@No Guest,
I think you're confusing the issue of "appropriate to the forum" with "access".  If the government banned publication of this article, that would be censorship.  But privately controlled media always have editorial control over what they publish. The authors of thei withdrawn article are absolutely free to say whatever they want.  They just can't say it in a "medical" or "science" journal, because it's not science, it's a political editorial.  

A publication calling itself a "medical" or "science" journal has a reputation to protect, and it can only do so by limiting its content to articles backed up by data and accepted research protocols.  I think the editor, in this case, confused the popular definition of the word "hypothesis" with the scientific definition, and that was a huge error on his part.  I would have done the same thing if I were Elsevier. The authors of the retracted article are free to find a less scientific forum for their commentary.  For example, the Wall Street Journal or a Dallas newspaper would probably publish it, and the authors stand an excellent chance of landing interviews on Fox news.

